ce:section.ce:para:
First, we studied the effects of pH on the adsorption performance of the composite aerogel. As seen from the bar graph, the adsorption performance of the material is strongest at a pH of 6. Both the adsorption properties and fluorescence intensity of the composites are reduced under strong acidic conditions (Fig. 8
                     A). This is because the functional groups such as carboxyl, aldehyde, and amino groups on the surface of CQDs and NFC increase the degree of protonation under acidic conditions. Thus, H ions occupy the adsorption active sites of the composite material instead of Cr3+, and the number and species of fluorescence groups is reduced [71–74]. At the same time, the reason for the lower adsorption capacity may also be that the adsorption sites are occupied by hydrogen ions rather than by metal cations. We then sampled the materials at different times and analyzed the adsorption kinetics. Specifically, adsorption occurs rapidly within the first 30 min and then gradually stabilizes after 60 min, whereas the adsorption rate increases with an increase in the solution ion concentration (Fig. 8B). This rapid adsorption ability should be attributed to the mesoporous structure of the aerogel. Although the correlation coefficients of the two kinetics models that were used to fit the adsorption data are all greater than 0.97 (Table 2
                     ), it is obvious that the pseudo-second-order model is more suitable for this adsorption process. With the pseudo-second-order model, the correlation coefficient (R2) is above 0.99, and t/qt is linear with respect to t (Fig. 8C). The fitting results show that the adsorption rate of the composite aerogel is dominated by chemisorption, and the adsorption rate should be related to the number of surface-active sites.
